Managing revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of the large French companies, our struggle for the development of economic intelligence would have been vain...
For more than a decade, the attitude of the management of large companies towards its employees reminds the position of companies towards consumers prior to the marketing revolution: it is a question of bringing employees to "values" determined above, as it used to be, to impose on consumers products designed by the factory technicians.
By placing the client at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has restored market conquest strategies to the spot... although the authoritarian temptation to impose unconnected products from customer preference factors returns regularly!
Employee demobilization can lead to mortal demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the emergent part of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects managers.
This demobilization seriously undermines the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, including R & D and, moreover, economic intelligence.
In fact, the EIA "requires all stakeholders ... a proactive approach and a prospective vision"; it requires employees a commitment that the authoritarian management revenues are completely offset.
That is why we call for a management revolution that would be to put employees at the centre of the business's concerns as well as the client.
All relative usefulness of internal opinion surveys
Will internal opinion surveys – such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – encourage this revolution in management practices?
Unfortunately, I fear not.
- First because I found that, in the face of a new situation, every structure finally comes, after many diversions, to do priority... what it has always done!
- Then because authoritarism – one of the pathologies of power – grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic vision of human behaviour.
Issus of major engineering schools, they have a mechanical interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, through intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the U.S. "neurosciences" and widely disseminated, to their unconsciousness, by the institutes of studies and the media.
Thus, suggesting that the "sic" of the leadership's commitment is possible, a recent Ipsos survey published in Le Figaro.fr strengthens the leaders in a mechanical governance position that is inappropriate to today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the management revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies requires the adoption of a finalist vision of human behaviour.
It consists of incorporating in any reasoning or practice of governance a fundamental finding: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means to achieve part of their dreams, ambitions, projects.
At present, only studies from the Reasonal Analysis adopt this concept of employee motivation.
These studies have shown that they judge their business on the basis of a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to assess what it offers them to achieve their life projects.
Thanks to the identification and measurement of these mobilization factors, business leaders can control, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and return their management of human resources "in the place".
They thus create a field favourable to the concerted development of robust and efficient economic intelligence.
