75 per cent of mothers working had occupational problems due to their maternity
Discrimination at work has increased over the past few years, especially for young-generation women who want to be mothers.
This is what the study "Federalism and career of women in Spain", carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Institute of Mujer, reveals.
The survey, conducted on 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, leaves no room for doubt: 75 per cent of the mothers working have seen their career limited due to maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences in the beginning of coupled life and the number of children, whether women work or not and the type of employment employed.
Those who don't work outside the home, work part-time or have a little stable work, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, are pushing back entry into couple life and first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women aged 35 to 49 with fixed work have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after being coupled. This figure goes to 4.1 among those working in the public sector. "The data show that women with stable employment needed more time in their lives to get it, which has led them to delay the union and arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exercises have a major influence on maternity, but less on the date of common start of life," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that widens the gap between the age of marriage of women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they marry and have their first child late.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49-year-old group, those who completed basic and higher studies were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 on average.
"A further disctipation also occurs between women, depending on their level of study.
While those who have completed basic studies marry and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have completed medium- or higher-level studies reverse this program and give priority to obtaining stable work as a precondition for marriage and the arrival of a child," says Mrs. Delgado.
