Emergency braking aid is now mandatory
As this happened with the ABS brake antiblocking system and as will happen with the ESP stability control, emergency braking aid systems will be a mandatory element on European cars.
They are already mandatory on newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a shortage period has been fixed until the end of February 2011.
The aim of the measure imposed by the European Union is to strengthen the protection of pedestrians, even if, by its way of action, it can also help to avoid many rear shocks.
The emergency braking assistant shall act by increasing the pressure on the brakes in case of emergency detected by the system thanks to the driver’s footstep.
But the latter does not always maintain pressure until the end.
According to a study carried out by the manufacturer of Bosch car components, one third of the drivers involved in an accident had not been able to push the brake before the collision, and half of them had not benefited from all their strength.
Up to 1 100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, in revanch, requires the maximum of the brake system, reducing the distance the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with such elements, up to 1 100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided every year.
